WEBVTT

00:02.370 --> 00:10.611
**

00:10.644 --> 00:19.087
**

00:19.120 --> 00:22.423
[ Siren wails in distance ]

00:22.456 --> 00:24.292
[ Keyboard taps ]

00:24.325 --> 00:26.527
Come on.
Is the system down?

00:26.560 --> 00:27.828
Worked fine for me.

00:27.861 --> 00:30.164
[ Sighs ]
I don't have time for this.

00:30.198 --> 00:31.132
How you doing?

00:31.165 --> 00:32.833
The computer
is not working.

00:32.866 --> 00:35.103
That's not
what I'm talking about.

00:35.136 --> 00:37.071
I know. I'm fine.

00:37.105 --> 00:39.807
A patient died
because of something you did.

00:39.840 --> 00:43.611
I think it's safe to say the
one thing you are not is "fine."

00:43.644 --> 00:44.745
I'm dealing.

00:44.778 --> 00:47.181
How exactly are you dealing?

00:47.215 --> 00:48.849
I'm getting back to work,

00:48.882 --> 00:51.519
I have a diabetic toe
to debride,

00:51.552 --> 00:54.388
and I'm putting it
behind me.

00:54.422 --> 00:58.392
How do you do that --
put it behind you?

00:58.426 --> 01:00.494
By moving forward.

01:00.528 --> 01:02.663
I appreciate your concern.
You're welcome.

01:02.696 --> 01:06.200
I'm gonna make an appointment
for you for grief counseling.

01:06.234 --> 01:09.537
Dr. Mohan -- She's an expert
in dealing with hospital staff

01:09.570 --> 01:13.674
who have experienced
stressful events.

01:13.707 --> 01:15.643
That's not necessary.

01:15.676 --> 01:19.247
You agree
you had a "stressful event"?

01:19.280 --> 01:23.317
And while I am comforted by your
commitment to move forward

01:23.351 --> 01:24.718
by not looking back,

01:24.752 --> 01:26.720
I still want you
to see Dr. Mohan.

01:26.754 --> 01:29.157
[ Inhales sharply ]
If she says that you are fine,

01:29.190 --> 01:31.459
then -- and only then --
can you go back to surgery.

01:31.492 --> 01:33.427
[ Keyboard clacks ]
It's working now.

01:33.461 --> 01:35.729
You just have to be
patient.

01:35.763 --> 01:40.368
**

01:40.401 --> 01:41.502
[ Monitor beeping ]

01:41.535 --> 01:42.836
Heart rate 36.

01:42.870 --> 01:45.406
Push another five milligrams of
morphine and prep a nitro drip.

01:45.439 --> 01:46.940
We need atropine
on board stat.

01:46.974 --> 01:49.843
What do you got for me?
[ Exhales sharply ]
An MI with severe bradycardia.

01:49.877 --> 01:51.044
He's had aspirin, nitro,

01:51.078 --> 01:53.614
and now we're trying to give him
a real rate with atropine.

01:53.647 --> 01:54.615
Cardiology see him?

01:54.648 --> 01:55.749
He's got a broken pacemaker

01:55.783 --> 01:58.286
and probably needs his coronary
arteries cleared --

01:58.319 --> 02:00.521
feels like a triple bypass,
but you're the expert.

02:00.554 --> 02:03.424
BNP is sky high.

02:03.457 --> 02:04.825
What do you see?

02:04.858 --> 02:07.661
[ Sighs ] His ventricles
are barely pumping.

02:07.695 --> 02:10.231
He's had two massive
prior MIs.

02:10.264 --> 02:11.865
End stage heart failure.

02:11.899 --> 02:13.601
His heart's
way beyond repair.

02:13.634 --> 02:14.735
What are our options?

02:14.768 --> 02:15.869
He's 73 years old.

02:15.903 --> 02:18.739
His age is an absolute
contraindication for transplant.

02:18.772 --> 02:21.209
He's dying.
Well, he's not dead yet.

02:21.242 --> 02:22.343
What else?

02:22.376 --> 02:23.944
How about cardiac
resynchronization?

02:23.977 --> 02:25.946
That will get what's left of
both ventricles

02:25.979 --> 02:26.814
working together.

02:26.847 --> 02:27.715
A biventricular pacer?

02:27.748 --> 02:29.450
It should make him feel
a little better

02:29.483 --> 02:31.519
[Sighs] in the few months
he's got left.

02:31.552 --> 02:32.820
[ Monitor beeping rapidly ]

02:32.853 --> 02:34.855
His rate drops any lower,
he'll arrest.

02:34.888 --> 02:37.525
Claire, prep his jugular to
float in a temporary pacemaker.

02:37.558 --> 02:38.659
Shaun,
call up to the cath lab

02:38.692 --> 02:40.628
and have them get an estimate
on how long it'll take

02:40.661 --> 02:41.862
to get the bi-pacer
in house.

02:41.895 --> 02:49.470
**

02:49.503 --> 02:50.671
Something wrong?

02:50.704 --> 02:51.672
Um, not at all.

02:51.705 --> 02:53.641
Just a little bit too much
coffee this morning.

02:53.674 --> 02:55.443
Let's go. Do it now.

02:55.476 --> 03:02.250
**

03:02.283 --> 03:06.287
[ Heavy breathing, grunting ]

03:06.320 --> 03:07.221
Restraints, please!

03:07.255 --> 03:08.922
I don't want to get stuck
with a needle.

03:08.956 --> 03:15.263
**

03:15.296 --> 03:17.231
You're scaring him.

03:17.265 --> 03:22.303
**

03:22.336 --> 03:23.537
[ Yells ]

03:23.571 --> 03:24.772
You're scaring him.

03:24.805 --> 03:26.907
Nurse:
Haldol, five milligrams.

03:26.940 --> 03:28.509
You're scaring him!

03:28.542 --> 03:30.411
Who are you?
Dr. Shaun Murphy.

03:30.444 --> 03:32.580
This patient is psychotic,
Dr. Murphy.

03:32.613 --> 03:34.782
He's not psychotic.

03:36.417 --> 03:39.453
You don't like people
touching you.

03:41.722 --> 03:44.925
He's not psychotic.
He's autistic.

03:46.960 --> 03:49.930
-- Captions by VITAC --

03:49.963 --> 03:58.539
**

04:01.675 --> 04:04.345
Shaun: You're being
an excellent patient.

04:06.380 --> 04:08.616
Okay. We're finished.

04:08.649 --> 04:11.919
You're s-same as...

04:11.952 --> 04:14.522
me.

04:14.555 --> 04:17.625
Can we release his hands?

04:17.658 --> 04:20.994
Dr. Murphy? His hands?

04:21.028 --> 04:24.064
I'm here, son --
Mom and Dad are here.

04:24.097 --> 04:26.800
You can let go of his hands.
He won't hurt you.

04:30.638 --> 04:33.707
Wrong stop.
Wrong stop.

04:33.741 --> 04:35.376
Can someone tell me
what happened?

04:35.409 --> 04:39.680
Liam has a 5.4 centimeter
laceration on his forehead,

04:39.713 --> 04:41.582
probably from a fall.

04:41.615 --> 04:43.384
The wound was infiltrated

04:43.417 --> 04:46.354
with five milliliters
of 1% lidocaine...

04:46.387 --> 04:51.859
7 -- 7 single-interrupted
5-0 Prolene sutures.

04:51.892 --> 04:52.893
He will a small scar,

04:52.926 --> 04:55.363
but no other long-term effects
from this injury.

04:55.396 --> 04:56.930
You're my son's doctor.

04:56.964 --> 05:00.768
I am. Dr. Shaun Murphy --
"Shaun" with a U.

05:00.801 --> 05:03.804
Got lost -- got lost, got lost,
got lost, got lost!

05:03.837 --> 05:06.840
Yes, yes. Yes.
But you're okay.
Got lost.
Got lost, got lost.

05:08.041 --> 05:09.710
You won't be taking that bus
again.

05:09.743 --> 05:11.111
Don:
This light is too bright.

05:11.144 --> 05:13.581
These rooms make him anxious.
Can we take him home?

05:13.614 --> 05:14.815
No.

05:14.848 --> 05:15.849
Your son is jaundiced,

05:15.883 --> 05:18.686
clenching his right abdominal
muscles when touched

05:18.719 --> 05:19.587
and febrile.

05:19.620 --> 05:20.788
He should not go home.

05:20.821 --> 05:26.026
**

05:26.059 --> 05:29.863
[ Monitor beeping ]

05:31.832 --> 05:33.667
Why am I here?

05:33.701 --> 05:35.936
Your pacemaker malfunctioned.

05:35.969 --> 05:37.505
You had a heart attack.

05:37.538 --> 05:40.408
I...I think
I get that part.

05:40.441 --> 05:41.509
[ Inhales sharply ]

05:41.542 --> 05:42.810
Your neighbor's gardener

05:42.843 --> 05:45.379
saw you on the ground
inside your house --

05:45.413 --> 05:47.915
called 911,
saved your life.

05:47.948 --> 05:52.853
Well, I must remember
to thank him.

05:53.821 --> 05:56.957
How old are you?

05:56.990 --> 05:58.091
Me?

05:58.125 --> 06:00.794
I know how old I am.

06:00.828 --> 06:03.030
I'm 28.

06:03.063 --> 06:05.833
We have, uh, a biventricular
pacer on its way,

06:05.866 --> 06:08.536
and it's gonna make you feel
a lot better.

06:08.569 --> 06:10.804
Is it?

06:12.673 --> 06:15.643
I will be back to prep you
for surgery.

06:16.877 --> 06:19.713
Liam has elevated bilirubin
and liver enzymes,

06:19.747 --> 06:21.549
a white cell count of 23.

06:21.582 --> 06:25.953
Abdominal ultrasound shows
dilatation of the bile ducts.

06:25.986 --> 06:28.088
Sounds like
ascending cholangitis --

06:28.121 --> 06:29.022
can lead to sepsis

06:29.056 --> 06:31.692
if the bacteria gain access
to his blood.

06:31.725 --> 06:32.860
Is he stable now?

06:32.893 --> 06:35.062
Yes, his vital signs
are stable.

06:35.095 --> 06:37.898
Cause could be anything
from cancer to diet, so --

06:37.931 --> 06:40.901
Liam's parents have him
on a special ketogenic diet.

06:40.934 --> 06:43.170
High-fat diets can cause
obstructive gallstones,

06:43.203 --> 06:44.972
which could have set
the whole thing off.

06:45.005 --> 06:46.707
Do an ERCP to clear him.

06:46.740 --> 06:49.009
After that, a few weeks
of broad spectrum antibiotics

06:49.042 --> 06:50.143
should take care of things.

06:50.177 --> 06:52.145
[ Footsteps departing ]

07:00.488 --> 07:06.760
**

07:06.794 --> 07:13.066
**

07:13.100 --> 07:15.569
Shaun:
I want you help.

07:15.603 --> 07:18.606
[ Clears throat ]
With what?

07:18.639 --> 07:21.141
Endoscopic Retrograde
Cholangio-Pancreatography.

07:21.174 --> 07:25.178
ERCP? Why?

07:25.212 --> 07:27.247
You've done those before,
Shaun.

07:27.280 --> 07:30.851
You're good with people
who have autism.

07:35.255 --> 07:40.127
Okay, Glen,
let's get this, star...ted

07:40.160 --> 07:42.195
Glen, you almost finished?

07:44.698 --> 07:47.835
It's Dr. Kalu.

07:47.868 --> 07:49.236
Glen?

07:49.269 --> 07:55.108
**

07:55.142 --> 08:00.948
**

08:00.981 --> 08:02.215
Yeah, we have a code green.

08:02.249 --> 08:05.252
Patient is Caucasian, male,
185 pounds.

08:05.285 --> 08:08.255
[ Breathing rapidly ]

08:08.288 --> 08:15.663
**

08:15.696 --> 08:17.598
Shaun, can you talk to him
or something?

08:17.631 --> 08:19.099
I can't push the Midazolam.

08:23.136 --> 08:25.639
Four lights...four doors.

08:25.673 --> 08:27.274
Yes. Lots of things.

08:27.307 --> 08:31.779
32 and 8. 32, 8.

08:31.812 --> 08:34.882
32 is the number
of cabinet windows,

08:34.915 --> 08:36.850
and 8 is the number
of handles.

08:38.986 --> 08:40.020
[ Monitor beeping ]

08:40.053 --> 08:41.989
Hmm, the end title's CO2
is rising.

08:42.022 --> 08:44.658
He needs oxygen.
He has respiratory depression.

08:44.692 --> 08:47.795
It's a common reaction
to Midazolam.

08:47.828 --> 08:50.831
[ Beeping steadies ]

08:52.633 --> 08:54.768
CO2 is coming down.

08:54.802 --> 08:57.270
You can proceed, Claire.
Thank you.

09:05.145 --> 09:09.116
Have you been around
a lot of other autistic people?

09:09.149 --> 09:11.051
I've never met someone
with autism.

09:11.084 --> 09:12.620
Oh.

09:12.653 --> 09:14.922
So, it must be nice to spend
some time around Liam, then.

09:14.955 --> 09:16.590
[ Scoffing ] Why?

09:16.624 --> 09:20.093
[ Normal voice ]
Why would that be nice?

09:20.127 --> 09:23.597
Okay.

09:23.631 --> 09:26.233
There are no stones.

09:26.266 --> 09:28.736
Where are the stones?

09:28.769 --> 09:30.704
And there is scarring.

09:30.738 --> 09:33.206
This has nothing to do
with gallstones.

09:33.240 --> 09:35.743
The entire biliary tree is so
thick with scarring

09:35.776 --> 09:38.679
we can't even
get the camera through.

09:43.884 --> 09:45.919
The differential diagnosis for
biliary tree scarring includes

09:45.953 --> 09:49.857
primary sclerosing cholangitis,
liver failure,

09:49.890 --> 09:51.959
secondary to primary
biliary cirrhosis --

09:51.992 --> 09:54.795
Yeah, Shaun, we can add a few
cancers to that list as well --

09:54.828 --> 09:56.196
It's a long and ugly one.

09:56.229 --> 09:58.732
Find another way
to figure out what it is.

09:58.766 --> 09:59.900
We could do
an MRI.

09:59.933 --> 10:03.370
No, we couldn't.

10:03.403 --> 10:04.437
It's not possible.

10:04.471 --> 10:06.173
That's the first time
I've ever heard you say that.

10:06.206 --> 10:07.875
-Liam is stimming.
-Stimming?

10:07.908 --> 10:11.044
The tics and spasms are a
neurological response to stress.

10:11.078 --> 10:12.846
If he's doing an MRI,
there is stress --

10:12.880 --> 10:14.414
if there is stress,
he won't keep still,

10:14.447 --> 10:16.316
if he wont' keep still,
we can't do an MRI.

10:16.349 --> 10:17.350
Therefore,
it is impossible.

10:17.384 --> 10:19.386
Maybe if you just keep talking
to him like that,

10:19.419 --> 10:22.322
he'll doze off
and it'll all be simple.

10:22.355 --> 10:24.024
Give him a mild sedative.

10:24.057 --> 10:26.259
He didn't respond well
to Midazolam during ERCP --

10:26.293 --> 10:27.527
depresses his breathing.

10:27.560 --> 10:30.430
His respiratory saturation can't
be properly monitored inside --

10:30.463 --> 10:31.464
I get it.

10:31.498 --> 10:33.366
He could die in the MRI
and we wouldn't know.

10:33.400 --> 10:35.268
You're just gonna have to find
a different way to calm him.

10:35.302 --> 10:37.337
Okay. We'll do it.

10:37.370 --> 10:38.706
Guess he has an idea.

10:38.739 --> 10:41.108
[ Scoffs ]

10:41.141 --> 10:42.710
Loudspeaker:
We have a code green.

10:42.743 --> 10:46.413
Patient is a Caucasian male,
73 years of age.

10:48.348 --> 10:50.684
Shaun,
what are you doing?

10:50.718 --> 10:52.185
Counting.

10:52.219 --> 10:54.121
Counting what?
Hmm. Distance.

10:54.154 --> 10:56.256
Why?

10:56.289 --> 10:59.893
I want $1,643.

10:59.927 --> 11:01.729
You can get that
by counting?

11:01.762 --> 11:06.033
That's why you're alone
and pacing in this room?

11:06.066 --> 11:07.134
What do you want the money
for?

11:07.167 --> 11:10.403
I want to buy a television.
$1,600 for a television?

11:10.437 --> 11:13.073
And 43. I am a surgeon.
I get paychecks.

11:13.106 --> 11:15.442
You're not a surgeon yet.
You're a surgical resident.

11:15.475 --> 11:18.211
Ah, there's a big difference
in the paycheck there, pal.

11:18.245 --> 11:20.347
I'm not a child, pal.

11:20.380 --> 11:22.115
[ Sighs ]

11:22.149 --> 11:24.251
How 'bout $1,000
for a television?

11:24.284 --> 11:27.220
No. The one I want is $1,643,
okay?

11:27.254 --> 11:29.089
I know,
but you have a budget.

11:29.122 --> 11:33.226
A budget.
You -- Uh, rent, food,
bills to pay.

11:34.461 --> 11:37.765
I should do my own budget.
I have an MRI to do.

11:37.798 --> 11:43.971
**

11:44.004 --> 11:47.407
These are live feeds --
entrances, E.R., receiving dock.

11:47.440 --> 11:49.109
If your patient had left,
we would've seen it.

11:49.142 --> 11:50.277
Then where'd he go?

11:50.310 --> 11:52.913
A freight elevator, but we don't
have cams in the freights,

11:52.946 --> 11:53.914
and he doesn't pop back up.

11:53.947 --> 11:58.919
So, we're dealing with
an alien abduction here?

12:00.153 --> 12:01.521
Sorry.

12:01.554 --> 12:03.423
We don't have cams
on the freight elevators

12:03.456 --> 12:05.425
on levels one, four
and five, and the basement.

12:05.458 --> 12:07.094
And you got people
looking on those floors?

12:07.127 --> 12:09.062
We've covered four and five,
and we're moving on to one.

12:09.096 --> 12:11.431
[ Exhales sharply ]

12:15.302 --> 12:17.938
[ Cellphone chimes ]

12:23.576 --> 12:26.246
[ Cellphone clacking ]

12:30.517 --> 12:33.553
[ Cellphone chimes ]

12:33.586 --> 12:35.388
[ Doors open ]

12:35.422 --> 12:38.358
[ Exhales sharply ]
Hey.

12:39.426 --> 12:40.427
What's in the basement?

12:40.460 --> 12:41.795
[ Doors close ]
[ Clears throat ]

12:41.829 --> 12:43.263
Pediatric patient
lost a blanket --

12:43.296 --> 12:44.998
I'm just gonna check
lost and found.

12:45.032 --> 12:47.534
That's nice of you.

12:49.469 --> 12:50.537
While you're there,

12:50.570 --> 12:54.441
you might want to check
if they found your code green.

12:54.474 --> 12:58.778
[ Doors open ]

13:02.315 --> 13:05.352
[ Breathing heavily ]

13:07.187 --> 13:10.390
Uh, this is Doctor...

13:10.423 --> 13:12.225
This is Shaun.

13:12.259 --> 13:14.494
I an hear you
when you speak.

13:14.527 --> 13:17.397
I was thinking
about something.

13:17.430 --> 13:23.270
There are 24 steps
from the ambulance to the E.R.

13:24.604 --> 13:28.341
Please turn down the lights.
That helps calm him.

13:29.509 --> 13:34.414
There are 24 steps
from the ambulance to the E.R.

13:35.315 --> 13:41.588
There are 22 steps from
the ambulance to the E.R.

13:41.621 --> 13:43.991
He has very long strides.

13:44.024 --> 13:45.225
Yes.

13:45.258 --> 13:51.064
There are 22 steps
from the ambulance to the E.R.

13:53.400 --> 13:56.303
[ Whirring ]

13:56.336 --> 14:01.441
There are 37 steps
from the elevator to room 405.

14:01.474 --> 14:04.511
There are 37 steps

14:04.544 --> 14:08.982
from the elevator
to room 405.

14:09.016 --> 14:13.620
In room 405,
there are 6 steps to the sink...

14:13.653 --> 14:15.989
6 steps to the sink.

14:16.023 --> 14:18.425
Claire:
We're getting good images.

14:18.458 --> 14:23.931
It's amazing how accomplished
you are for someone with ASD.

14:23.964 --> 14:25.999
Three steps to the window.

14:26.033 --> 14:26.967
Three steps to --

14:27.000 --> 14:28.335
[ Mechanical buzzing ]

14:28.368 --> 14:29.469
Three...

14:29.502 --> 14:31.905
[ Breathing intensifies ]

14:31.939 --> 14:35.909
It's seven steps --
It's seven steps to the door.

14:35.943 --> 14:39.146
Liam, there are seven steps
to the door.

14:40.647 --> 14:41.681
You need to get him out.

14:41.714 --> 14:42.983
Just a little more time.

14:43.016 --> 14:45.285
He's scared.
It's okay to be scared.
We need to finish this.

14:45.318 --> 14:47.487
Seven --
You're doing wonderfully,
honey.

14:47.520 --> 14:51.391
Just breathe.
Just breathe.

14:51.424 --> 14:54.494
No, it's seven steps
to the door.

14:54.527 --> 14:57.697
[ Screams ]

14:57.730 --> 15:01.568
[ Heavy breathing continues ]

15:07.674 --> 15:09.476
[ Elevator chimes ]

15:19.452 --> 15:21.554
Glen?

15:27.094 --> 15:29.162
Glen?

15:34.301 --> 15:35.702
Glen?

15:35.735 --> 15:39.472
[ Glen coughs ]

15:40.473 --> 15:42.075
Glen?

15:42.109 --> 15:44.711
[ Coughs ]
It's Dr. Kalu.

15:44.744 --> 15:46.413
Let's get you upstairs.

15:46.446 --> 15:47.214
Go away.

15:47.247 --> 15:49.516
We're gonna
get your new pacer in.

15:49.549 --> 15:53.086
Don't you get it?

15:53.120 --> 15:56.623
I broke my pacer on purpose.

15:56.656 --> 15:59.092
I want to die.

15:59.126 --> 16:03.530
**

16:08.101 --> 16:10.237
With a new pacemaker,
maybe you'll feel better.

16:10.270 --> 16:12.339
So, I'll be cured?

16:12.372 --> 16:13.706
Good as new?

16:13.740 --> 16:15.242
Heh.

16:15.275 --> 16:17.077
Well, it'll reduce your pain,
and then hopefully --

16:17.110 --> 16:19.312
You think this is
the first time I've heard that?

16:19.346 --> 16:21.548
It's always
the "next best thing."

16:21.581 --> 16:24.251
[ Coughs ]

16:24.284 --> 16:28.421
The truth is
I'll just keep getting worse.

16:28.455 --> 16:30.457
I know it, you know it.

16:30.490 --> 16:32.225
Do you have any family
you can talk to?

16:32.259 --> 16:35.462
Brother's dead.
I don't have a wife.

16:35.495 --> 16:40.233
So, no, there's no one around to
nag me into doing what you want.

16:40.267 --> 16:42.535
We have great
counseling services here.

16:42.569 --> 16:45.605
[ Sighs ]
I'm in pain, 28 --

16:45.638 --> 16:46.706
all the time.

16:46.739 --> 16:49.542
Talk therapy
gonna talk that away?

16:49.576 --> 16:50.610
Let's get you upstairs.

16:50.643 --> 16:52.512
You color's not good,
and your lungs are crackling,

16:52.545 --> 16:54.081
which means
there's fluid building in --

16:54.114 --> 16:55.648
I know my...

16:55.682 --> 16:56.749
I know my rights.

16:56.783 --> 17:00.287
I don't have to get treatment
if I don't want it.

17:00.320 --> 17:02.722
The minute I catch my breath,
I'm gonna walk out of here,

17:02.755 --> 17:06.659
so you can just leave.

17:06.693 --> 17:14.201
**

17:14.234 --> 17:15.835
I'm not leaving.

17:15.868 --> 17:21.141
**

17:21.174 --> 17:25.178
[ Exhales sharply ]

17:28.415 --> 17:30.550
We can't treat it until
we find the underlying cause.

17:30.583 --> 17:31.684
How do you do that?

17:31.718 --> 17:35.188
Surgically -- It's called
"exploratory laparoscopy."

17:35.222 --> 17:38.591
We use a camera to navigate
Liam's midsection.

17:38.625 --> 17:41.561
There are
significant risks --

17:41.594 --> 17:43.330
perforation of an organ,

17:43.363 --> 17:45.832
accidental spread
seeding malignancy.

17:45.865 --> 17:47.300
And you have to do this

17:47.334 --> 17:49.636
because he can't stay still
during an MRI?

17:49.669 --> 17:51.671
You obviously know your son
better than I do.

17:51.704 --> 17:53.273
Do you think
we should try again?

17:53.306 --> 18:00.213
**

18:00.247 --> 18:07.187
**

18:07.220 --> 18:14.161
**

18:14.194 --> 18:16.363
So, Shaun told me
he's getting a TV --

18:16.396 --> 18:18.365
70 inches, all the works.

18:18.398 --> 18:19.666
Is he now?

18:19.699 --> 18:21.134
It's just a TV.

18:21.168 --> 18:22.469
It's not about a TV.

18:22.502 --> 18:24.304
Why are you so worried
about him?

18:24.337 --> 18:26.439
He showed up late for work
half a dozen times,

18:26.473 --> 18:27.874
he calls me
2:00 in the morning

18:27.907 --> 18:29.676
'cause he can't find
a screwdriver,

18:29.709 --> 18:32.779
and his superintendent wants to
kick him out of his building.

18:32.812 --> 18:34.314
Did you show up?
What?

18:34.347 --> 18:35.648
At 2:00 in the morning
when he called you

18:35.682 --> 18:37.717
about a lost screwdriver,

18:37.750 --> 18:39.352
did you show up?

18:39.386 --> 18:40.187
He was frantic.

18:40.220 --> 18:42.322
I didn't know
what he was gonna do.

18:42.355 --> 18:43.756
There are 47 residents
here,

18:43.790 --> 18:45.492
and all of them show up late
sometimes,

18:45.525 --> 18:46.526
all of them make mistakes,

18:46.559 --> 18:48.561
and hopefully,
all of them learn.

18:48.595 --> 18:51.231
If you want to worry
about Shaun, fine.

18:51.264 --> 18:55.168
But you fought to hire him
because you know he can learn.

18:55.202 --> 18:58.805
The question is,
are you willing to let him?

18:58.838 --> 19:08.848
**

19:08.881 --> 19:09.882
Shaun?

19:09.916 --> 19:12.685
I can see the pixelation.

19:12.719 --> 19:15.755
That's great. Listen --
It's not great.

19:15.788 --> 19:17.590
Mm, it's not good.

19:17.624 --> 19:18.925
On a high-quality display,

19:18.958 --> 19:22.462
the human eye at 20/20
cannot detect the pixels.

19:23.863 --> 19:28.701
[ Remote control thuds ]
You disappeared
after the failed MRI.

19:29.336 --> 19:30.770
I failed.

19:30.803 --> 19:34.807
Yeah, see,
I don't think it's about that.

19:34.841 --> 19:37.977
You were hesitant with this kid
even before that.

19:38.010 --> 19:41.448
You asked me to the ERCP.

19:41.481 --> 19:44.817
Doctors don't have to like their
patients, Claire.

19:45.952 --> 19:48.288
You don't like him?
I don't know him.

19:48.321 --> 19:50.757
Shaun, there's something else
going on here.

19:50.790 --> 19:54.561
I know you know that.
No. Nu-- Nu-huh.

19:54.594 --> 19:56.729
He has the same condition
you have.

19:56.763 --> 19:58.765
You have never met
anyone with --

19:58.798 --> 20:01.601
Do you like all people
with psoriasis?

20:02.669 --> 20:04.471
[ Scoffs ] I don't have --

20:04.504 --> 20:05.905
Yes, you do.

20:05.938 --> 20:08.375
And you can never
get rid of it.

20:08.408 --> 20:09.141
Okay.

20:09.175 --> 20:11.678
It's too bad
you don't like him,

20:11.711 --> 20:14.013
because
I think he likes you.

20:14.046 --> 20:16.416
Not only that,
I think he looks up to you.

20:16.449 --> 20:18.718
So you know how he thinks?

20:18.751 --> 20:21.954
Well, not as much
as you probably do.

20:21.988 --> 20:27.760
**

20:27.794 --> 20:30.763
What are you waiting for?

20:30.797 --> 20:34.401
For you to pass out.

20:34.434 --> 20:36.803
Judging by
the size your ankles...

20:36.836 --> 20:38.538
[ Clicks tongue ]

20:38.571 --> 20:39.939
...that shouldn't be
too long from now.

20:39.972 --> 20:43.042
Then hopefully I can get you
upstairs before you die.

20:43.075 --> 20:46.746
Why do you give such a damn
about what I do with my life?

20:46.779 --> 20:49.482
I don't know, Glen.

20:49.516 --> 20:52.785
Why'd you want to die
so bad?

20:56.923 --> 20:59.392
I've lived.

20:59.426 --> 21:00.993
I've had decent jobs,

21:01.027 --> 21:03.430
and I've had jobs
that went nowhere.

21:03.463 --> 21:05.398
[ Inhales, exhales ]

21:05.432 --> 21:07.334
Had a good roof
over my head,

21:07.367 --> 21:10.036
and I've had that good roof
taken away from me.

21:10.069 --> 21:14.006
I loved a girl,
and I got married.

21:14.040 --> 21:18.845
The 20 happiest years
of my life...

21:18.878 --> 21:21.781
then she died.

21:21.814 --> 21:24.751
And now I'm alone

21:24.784 --> 21:26.553
and in pain.

21:26.586 --> 21:28.488
[ Chuckles ]

21:28.521 --> 21:33.593
Feels like
the end of the story.

21:36.128 --> 21:37.530
I understand.

21:37.564 --> 21:39.599
Yeah?

21:39.632 --> 21:43.936
You've had some tough times,
too, 28?

21:43.970 --> 21:47.073
Nobody understands
what it's like

21:47.106 --> 21:50.710
to be so good-looking
and successful?

21:50.743 --> 21:52.979
I was raised by nannies
and housekeepers.

21:53.012 --> 21:54.647
Oh, my God.

21:54.681 --> 21:55.915
You're an ass.

21:55.948 --> 21:57.717
Your point is
you didn't suffer

21:57.750 --> 21:59.919
because you were good-looking
and smart --

21:59.952 --> 22:04.691
you suffered
because you were rich?

22:06.393 --> 22:08.461
The only time I ever saw
my parents was Christmas.

22:08.495 --> 22:11.598
Seriously,
the story continues?

22:11.631 --> 22:13.600
They had this big party
every year,

22:13.633 --> 22:16.936
and wherever they were traveling
they'd always fly home for it.

22:16.969 --> 22:20.139
And I'd have to come home,
too,

22:20.172 --> 22:23.743
from whatever school
they sent me off to.

22:23.776 --> 22:28.515
When I was 18,
I decided that I was fed up.

22:28.548 --> 22:32.419
I was a man,
done being their son.

22:32.452 --> 22:34.387
[ Chuckles ]

22:34.421 --> 22:37.023
And I was gonna tell them
publicly,

22:37.056 --> 22:40.126
tell all their friends what
horrible people they were.

22:40.159 --> 22:42.161
So I came home from school,
and I knocked on the door,

22:42.194 --> 22:45.798
and someone answered.

22:45.832 --> 22:48.935
But it wasn't my parents.
It was a stranger.

22:48.968 --> 22:51.938
Turns out they'd sold the house
months ago.

22:51.971 --> 22:54.140
They were gone.

22:56.543 --> 22:58.678
I guess they were done with me,
too.

22:58.711 --> 23:06.052
**

23:06.085 --> 23:07.119
[ Liam breathes heavily ]

23:07.153 --> 23:08.821
To prep Liam
for the laparoscopy,

23:08.855 --> 23:11.090
we need to make four small
incisions in his stomach.

23:11.123 --> 23:12.759
I don't need to do it.

23:12.792 --> 23:14.126
I-I don't need to do it.

23:14.160 --> 23:16.128
Liam, you do need to.
I don't need to!

23:16.162 --> 23:17.764
If you could just hold still
for a second, Liam.

23:17.797 --> 23:19.632
The -- the bus driver
lets me off.

23:19.666 --> 23:21.100
I-I get lost --

23:21.133 --> 23:22.001
You're safe now.

23:22.034 --> 23:23.503
I get lost. I'm hungry.

23:23.536 --> 23:24.637
I can't make food.

23:24.671 --> 23:27.774
C-C-Can't do bath --
Don't need to do it!

23:27.807 --> 23:31.778
C-C-Can't do food --
C-Can't put on clothes.

23:31.811 --> 23:32.712
Can't do bus.

23:32.745 --> 23:35.081
I took the bus.

23:37.049 --> 23:38.985
I got off
at the wrong stop,

23:39.018 --> 23:41.688
and I got scared,
but then I found my way.

23:41.721 --> 23:44.724
[ Breathing calms ]

23:44.757 --> 23:48.761
I did an MRI,
and a man got hurt.

23:48.795 --> 23:52.899
I made a mistake.
I make a lot of mistakes.

23:55.968 --> 23:58.070
You tried to walk.

23:58.104 --> 24:00.540
You made a mistake.

24:00.573 --> 24:05.011
But mistakes are good.
You should make more.

24:05.044 --> 24:06.646
You're like me.

24:06.679 --> 24:15.221
**

24:15.254 --> 24:18.224
You have red eyes --
uveitis.

24:18.257 --> 24:21.828
Liam takes vitamins -- Does Liam
also take herbal supplements?

24:21.861 --> 24:24.230
Kava root. Why?

24:24.263 --> 24:26.499
He doesn't need
the laparoscopic surgery.

24:26.533 --> 24:28.668
I know
what's wrong with him.

24:28.701 --> 24:31.771
The red eyes -- they're
caused by an immune flare-up,

24:31.804 --> 24:34.173
which can create the scarring
that we're seeing

24:34.206 --> 24:35.642
in his digestive system.

24:35.675 --> 24:37.109
The solution requires us
to go in

24:37.143 --> 24:39.679
and remove damaged segments
of the bowel piece by piece.

24:39.712 --> 24:40.747
Us?

24:40.780 --> 24:42.882
Yes, myself and my team.

24:42.915 --> 24:44.551
Is Dr. Murphy
on your team?

24:44.584 --> 24:46.653
Of course.

24:46.686 --> 24:51.090
Thank you
for diagnosing our son.

24:51.123 --> 24:55.695
Dr. Melendez, you have our
permission to do the surgery,

24:55.728 --> 24:59.031
but in no way
will Dr. Murphy be in it.

24:59.065 --> 25:07.540
**

25:09.876 --> 25:10.843
Well, the parents --
they won't budge.

25:10.877 --> 25:12.545
They don't believe
that anyone who has autism

25:12.579 --> 25:13.345
is capable do doing surgery.

25:13.379 --> 25:14.213
Well, clearly
they're irrational --

25:14.246 --> 25:16.015
I don't know --
shallow-minded people.

25:16.048 --> 25:17.283
Who cares?
What's the difference?

25:17.316 --> 25:19.852
You agree with them,
right?

25:19.886 --> 25:21.621
Do you agree with them?

25:21.654 --> 25:23.590
It's my team -- I don't want
anybody telling me

25:23.623 --> 25:25.725
who's supposed to be on my team,
including the Board.

25:25.758 --> 25:26.959
You're not answering
my question.

25:26.993 --> 25:29.896
The question's moot.
Moot? No, it's not.

25:29.929 --> 25:32.098
If you agree with them,
then the only issue

25:32.131 --> 25:34.634
is somebody stepping on
your poor, little toes.

25:34.667 --> 25:36.268
Get over it
and go save the kid.

25:36.302 --> 25:37.469
If you don't agree,

25:37.503 --> 25:40.072
if you think Shaun can handle
surgery, then tell them that.

25:40.106 --> 25:42.274
Tell them
to go screw themselves.

25:42.308 --> 25:44.977
Either they agree
that Dr. Murphy belongs

25:45.011 --> 25:47.847
in that room with you,
or you can go find them

25:47.880 --> 25:50.016
someplace else
to do the surgery.

25:50.049 --> 25:57.223
**

25:57.256 --> 26:00.627
I was an 18-year-old
with no one and no money.

26:00.660 --> 26:03.930
So I worked three jobs
and took out loans.

26:11.638 --> 26:14.173
Still alive.

26:15.742 --> 26:19.245
That's not a bad story, 28.

26:19.278 --> 26:22.982
What happened
with the parents?

26:23.015 --> 26:26.285
I talk to them now,
but...

26:26.318 --> 26:28.755
they're not the people
who got me here.

26:28.788 --> 26:31.257
It was the people
I didn't expect --

26:31.290 --> 26:34.126
the ex-Marine at the shelter
who got me my first job,

26:34.160 --> 26:35.928
and this crazy artist girl

26:35.962 --> 26:40.132
who convinced me to go after
what I really wanted.

26:41.668 --> 26:45.204
When you think you're alone,
Glen, you're not.

26:45.237 --> 26:51.010
**

26:51.043 --> 26:56.816
**

26:56.849 --> 26:59.318
All right.

26:59.351 --> 27:01.788
All right?

27:01.821 --> 27:06.859
**

27:06.893 --> 27:08.027
Ready?

27:08.060 --> 27:09.361
Two, three!

27:11.030 --> 27:14.834
No disturbing dreams?
[ Laughing ]
After a 36-hour shift?

27:14.867 --> 27:17.436
[ Normal voice ] From the moment
my head hits the pillow

27:17.469 --> 27:19.806
to the moment wake up,
all I see is black.

27:19.839 --> 27:22.875
Hm. How's your level
of concentration?

27:22.909 --> 27:24.443
Have you had
any difficulty focusing?

27:24.476 --> 27:25.678
I mean, I can do

27:25.712 --> 27:29.381
the New York Tim crossword
puzzle in one sitting.

27:31.851 --> 27:35.287
Sure, sometimes
I wish I was more focused.

27:35.321 --> 27:37.824
It's pretty normal,
right?

27:41.160 --> 27:43.229
Shaun's different.

27:43.262 --> 27:45.064
He also has savant syndrome.

27:45.097 --> 27:47.033
He has a remarkable memory.

27:47.066 --> 27:51.403
He has autism, same as
our son -- same limitations.

27:51.437 --> 27:53.472
Don: You saw what happened
to our son in the MRI --

27:53.505 --> 27:56.308
he knew he needed to lie still,
but he couldn't.

27:56.342 --> 27:59.311
Now, what happens if Dr. Murphy
breaks down like that

27:59.345 --> 28:02.381
while he's standing over my son
at an operating table?

28:02.414 --> 28:04.951
You know your son.

28:04.984 --> 28:07.186
I know surgeons.

28:07.219 --> 28:09.188
And after working
with Dr. Murphy,

28:09.221 --> 28:12.091
after challenging him in surgery
and everywhere else --

28:12.124 --> 28:15.728
probably more
than he deserved --

28:15.762 --> 28:19.398
I can tell you
he has my compete confidence.

28:19.431 --> 28:26.238
**

28:26.272 --> 28:28.074
I'm sorry.

28:28.107 --> 28:30.409
He doesn't have ours.

28:30.442 --> 28:33.445
So, what do we do now?

28:33.479 --> 28:36.415
I've contacted my colleague
at St. Joseph's,

28:36.448 --> 28:39.018
updated her
on Liam's condition.

28:39.051 --> 28:40.753
They have good people.

28:40.787 --> 28:42.288
We can arrange
for transportation

28:42.321 --> 28:43.255
as soon as possible.

28:43.289 --> 28:46.025
Where's my phone?
Have you seen my phone?

28:46.058 --> 28:48.895
Where's his second bag,
the one with his medications?

28:48.928 --> 28:51.931
I want...

28:51.964 --> 28:54.934
I want...

28:54.967 --> 28:56.769
What, honey?

28:56.803 --> 29:00.039
He said I could do it.

29:00.072 --> 29:03.042
I want Dr. Shaun.

29:03.075 --> 29:09.481
**

29:09.515 --> 29:10.349
Your pacemaker's here.

29:10.382 --> 29:12.418
The techs are programming it
as we speak.

29:12.451 --> 29:14.887
The moment they're ready,
we're gonna put it in.

29:14.921 --> 29:18.825
[ Monitor beeping ]

29:24.296 --> 29:26.866
[ Exhales, coughs ]

29:26.899 --> 29:31.403
I told you my wife died.

29:31.437 --> 29:36.475
The truth is
s-she left me.

29:36.508 --> 29:40.212
But I gave her good reason
for that,

29:40.246 --> 29:44.250
so I got what I deserved.

29:44.283 --> 29:48.587
We all make --
But you didn't get
what you deserved --

29:48.620 --> 29:53.225
good parents
who loved you.

29:53.259 --> 29:57.263
They were lucky to have you,
Jared.

29:57.296 --> 30:04.971
**

30:05.004 --> 30:12.444
**

30:12.478 --> 30:14.546
You appear remarkably
well-adjusted.

30:14.580 --> 30:15.514
Thank you.

30:15.547 --> 30:16.983
That's not a compliment.

30:17.016 --> 30:19.351
That's my concern.

30:19.385 --> 30:22.354
Well, I assume
everyone responds differently.

30:22.388 --> 30:27.126
The thing is
everyone responds.

30:27.159 --> 30:28.394
Strictly speaking,

30:28.427 --> 30:31.130
you don't meet the criteria to
be required to go into treatment

30:31.163 --> 30:33.199
or take a leave of absence,

30:33.232 --> 30:35.968
so I'm not gonna ground you.

30:39.906 --> 30:41.573
You're a strong woman,
Claire,

30:41.607 --> 30:44.476
and that strength has
undoubtedly played a major role

30:44.510 --> 30:47.513
in getting you
where you are.

30:47.546 --> 30:51.283
But if you have suppressed
feelings about this incident,

30:51.317 --> 30:54.020
you need to find someone
to share them with.

30:54.053 --> 30:56.956
Because if not,
they will eat you up

30:56.989 --> 30:59.325
no matter
how strong you are.

31:05.131 --> 31:08.167
All right, Glen.
Second ti--

31:09.435 --> 31:12.104
Oh, come on.

31:14.006 --> 31:16.308
[ Monitor beeping ]

31:16.342 --> 31:19.912
Thank you.

31:19.946 --> 31:21.948
It should be
a very interesting surgery.

31:21.981 --> 31:23.282
I'm glad I'm participating.

31:23.315 --> 31:26.152
[ Beeping quickens ]
[ Groans ]

31:26.185 --> 31:27.653
His pressure
is bottoming out.

31:27.686 --> 31:28.654
What's happening?

31:28.687 --> 31:30.456
His bowel
must have perforated.

31:30.489 --> 31:33.225
He's going into
septic shock.

31:37.663 --> 31:38.630
This perforation
could be anywhere.

31:38.664 --> 31:40.166
What's the best way to access
the entire bowel

31:40.199 --> 31:40.899
as quickly as possible?

31:40.933 --> 31:42.534
Full-length
midline incision.

31:42.568 --> 31:43.435
Good. Mark it.

31:43.469 --> 31:45.404
And what do we do
once we get in there?

31:45.437 --> 31:46.705
Eviscerate the entire bowel

31:46.738 --> 31:49.441
so we can check every inch
for necrotic segments.

31:49.475 --> 31:51.543
Okay,
let's make the cut.

31:51.577 --> 31:57.016
**

31:57.049 --> 31:58.650
You gonna take it or not?

31:58.684 --> 32:06.325
**

32:06.358 --> 32:14.033
**

32:14.066 --> 32:21.540
**

32:21.573 --> 32:24.076
This is the Number 3 L.

32:24.110 --> 32:26.545
It's made of high carbon steel.
It doesn't break.

32:26.578 --> 32:28.614
That's correct,
Dr. Murphy.

32:28.647 --> 32:35.154
**

32:35.187 --> 32:41.493
**

32:41.527 --> 32:44.230
Time of incision --
2:05 P.M.

32:44.263 --> 32:45.797
[ Cellphone vibrates ]
Loudspeaker:
We have a code green --

32:45.831 --> 32:49.235
patient is a Caucasian male,
73 years of age.
[ Cellphone beeps ]

32:49.268 --> 32:51.203
Where'd he go?

32:51.237 --> 32:53.239
Yeah, on my way.

32:53.272 --> 32:55.674
[ Cellphone beeps ]

32:55.707 --> 32:59.145
I have a five-centimeter segment
of proximal jejunum.

32:59.178 --> 33:01.613
It's...sclerotic,
but not perforated.

33:01.647 --> 33:03.549
All right,
mark it and move on.

33:03.582 --> 33:05.251
Shaun, why are you
just standing there?

33:05.284 --> 33:07.086
We have 25 feet of bowel
to run.

33:08.454 --> 33:11.557
Shaun, you need to get moving --
unless you've found something.

33:11.590 --> 33:13.459
I have --

33:13.492 --> 33:15.194
the perforation.
Clamp it off --

33:15.227 --> 33:16.495
I'll get in there
with the enterotomy scissors

33:16.528 --> 33:18.564
and remove
the damaged segment.

33:18.597 --> 33:20.999
I can't.

33:22.301 --> 33:24.303
You can't? Why not?

33:24.336 --> 33:26.472
It's a phlegmon.

33:26.505 --> 33:28.207
You found
a walled-off abscess?

33:28.240 --> 33:28.940
It's large.

33:28.974 --> 33:30.709
-Don't touch it.
-I already am.

33:30.742 --> 33:32.411
If you move
and that thing ruptures,

33:32.444 --> 33:34.246
the pus will spread to his
entire abdominal cavity --

33:34.280 --> 33:35.081
this boy dies.

33:35.114 --> 33:37.216
I know,
that's why I'm not moving.

33:37.249 --> 33:39.051
Claire, I need you
to open it up gently.

33:39.085 --> 33:40.652
I'm gonna evacuate
the septic contents,

33:40.686 --> 33:42.354
flush the cavity
with antibiotics,

33:42.388 --> 33:43.622
and then I'm gonna have you
remove the capsule.

33:43.655 --> 33:44.756
[ Monitor beeping rapidly ]

33:44.790 --> 33:46.192
I didn't do anything.

33:46.225 --> 33:47.226
That's the pressure tanking.

33:47.259 --> 33:49.495
You need to finish
what you're doing right now.

33:49.528 --> 33:51.263
[ Clears throat ]

33:52.631 --> 33:55.067
Let's go, Claire.
Come on.

33:57.769 --> 33:59.238
Clamp.

33:59.271 --> 34:02.108
Uh, you guys check left.

34:07.613 --> 34:09.248
[ Sighs ]

34:09.281 --> 34:12.084
Hey. Hey. Come on.

34:12.118 --> 34:14.453
Stop.

34:14.486 --> 34:16.822
Come on, Glen.

34:16.855 --> 34:18.190
We can do this.

34:18.224 --> 34:19.491
I don't want to --

34:19.525 --> 34:21.727
I just don't want to.

34:21.760 --> 34:24.263
Please leave me alone.

34:24.296 --> 34:29.101
Once I get my strength back,
I'll climb up and jump.

34:30.802 --> 34:33.339
I can't let you do that.

34:37.543 --> 34:40.279
[ Exhales sharply ]

34:43.549 --> 34:45.517
When
this temporary pacer fails,

34:45.551 --> 34:48.620
which it will,

34:48.654 --> 34:51.523
your heart may stop
and you die suddenly.

34:51.557 --> 34:52.758
But more likely, Glen,

34:52.791 --> 34:55.161
you slip back
into that slow rhythm,

34:55.194 --> 34:57.396
your chest is racked
with excruciating pain

34:57.429 --> 34:59.298
and your lungs
start to fill with fluid,

34:59.331 --> 35:00.432
and slowly you suffocate.

35:00.466 --> 35:02.768
Eh, give it a rest, 28.

35:02.801 --> 35:05.604
Just get me a DNR
and a cab.

35:05.637 --> 35:07.806
You can't help me.

35:07.839 --> 35:16.882
**

